WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.560
Welcome back to the Data Science Hangout.

00:00:14.560 --> 00:00:18.639
I was going to play around with a lesson I learned from Matt Dancho last week.

00:00:18.639 --> 00:00:22.240
If you've been here before, do you want to try putting a one in the chat?

00:00:22.240 --> 00:00:29.799
If it's your first time joining today, maybe put a two in the chat.

00:00:29.799 --> 00:00:33.639
It was fun seeing all the people commenting last week with Matt.

00:00:33.639 --> 00:00:36.759
But if it is your first time, it's so nice to meet you.

00:00:36.759 --> 00:00:37.880
I'm Rachel.

00:00:37.880 --> 00:00:43.240
This is an open space for the whole data science community to connect and chat about data science

00:00:43.240 --> 00:00:48.040
leadership, questions you're facing, and getting to learn about what's going on in the world of

00:00:48.040 --> 00:00:50.840
data science across different industries and companies.

00:00:51.799 --> 00:00:57.400
We share the recordings each week to our Posit YouTube, so you can always go back and rewatch

00:00:57.400 --> 00:00:59.080
or find helpful resources.

00:00:59.799 --> 00:01:06.599
These go up to the new Data Science Hangout site at Posit.co as well.

00:01:06.599 --> 00:01:12.519
I was a bit slow on this, but I just put up Jesse's and Marco's sessions as well this week.

00:01:13.400 --> 00:01:18.440
Together, we're all dedicated to creating a welcoming environment for everybody here,

00:01:18.440 --> 00:01:22.120
so we love when everyone can participate and we can hear from you all,

00:01:22.120 --> 00:01:25.720
no matter your level of experience or area of work.

00:01:26.519 --> 00:01:30.120
There's always three ways that you can jump in and ask questions or

00:01:30.919 --> 00:01:33.879
also provide your perspective on a point.

00:01:33.879 --> 00:01:35.400
It doesn't just have to be a question.

00:01:36.199 --> 00:01:38.919
You can jump in by raising your hand on Zoom here.

00:01:39.800 --> 00:01:44.279
You can put questions in the Zoom chat, and feel free to just put a little star next to it

00:01:44.279 --> 00:01:48.839
if it's something you want me to read out loud, if you're in a coffee shop or something like that.

00:01:49.800 --> 00:01:55.720
Then we also have a Slido link, which I forgot to share with Hannah ahead of time,

00:01:55.720 --> 00:02:01.559
so I'll copy that over in a second here and put that into the chat.

00:02:03.320 --> 00:02:03.879
There you go.

00:02:04.519 --> 00:02:07.400
With the Slido link, you can ask questions anonymously too.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:13.240
I am so excited to be joined by my co-host for today, Eric Nance.

00:02:13.240 --> 00:02:19.399
Eric is a director at Eli Lilly and Company, podcaster, and community builder

00:02:19.399 --> 00:02:23.080
that you may have seen around the open-source community a few times.

00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:28.919
He just celebrated his 100th podcast as well, so congrats, Eric.

00:02:28.919 --> 00:02:32.039
I would love to have you just jump in and introduce yourself

00:02:32.039 --> 00:02:34.520
and share a little bit about your role as well.

00:02:35.320 --> 00:02:39.000
Well, thank you so much, Rachel, and I'm really thrilled to be here.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:41.320
I've been watching the Hangout since the very beginning.

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:45.559
It's really an exciting space to be a part of and to be a co-host with you.

00:02:45.559 --> 00:02:47.080
It's tremendously exciting.

00:02:49.240 --> 00:02:54.679
My name is Eric, and I've been in my current role now as a director

00:02:54.679 --> 00:03:00.520
in the statistical innovation group at Lilly for over 12 years,

00:03:00.520 --> 00:03:03.000
which does not seem like a time that certainly flies,

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:07.479
but my day-to-day is a mix of a few things.

00:03:07.479 --> 00:03:11.160
I'm sure this will probably come up in the conversation,

00:03:11.160 --> 00:03:13.000
but I kind of wear a few hats.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:15.960
I'm a mini-manager, as they say.

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:18.199
I got a couple of direct reports in our group,

00:03:18.199 --> 00:03:21.479
and so I'm trying to help enable them to succeed.

00:03:21.479 --> 00:03:24.600
And where I put a lot of my focus time these days

00:03:24.600 --> 00:03:28.679
is bringing innovative algorithms and designs

00:03:28.679 --> 00:03:31.479
for the new clinical studies that we're trying to launch.

00:03:31.479 --> 00:03:37.160
And throughout all that process, the one tool that unifies everything is R.

00:03:37.160 --> 00:03:40.360
So literally, it is at the forefront of what I do,

00:03:40.360 --> 00:03:43.639
whether it's building Shiny apps, internal packages,

00:03:44.199 --> 00:03:47.160
consulting, and even with the community building

00:03:47.160 --> 00:03:48.679
that I'm sure we'll touch on as well.

00:03:49.639 --> 00:03:53.080
So I've been in a mix of a lot of different things at Lilly,

00:03:53.080 --> 00:03:55.000
but learned a lot along the way,

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:58.360
and certainly happy to share my insights of that.

00:03:58.360 --> 00:04:01.800
And yeah, it's always never a dull moment, as they say.

00:04:03.240 --> 00:04:04.199
That's awesome.

00:04:04.199 --> 00:04:05.399
And I forgot to ask you, Eric,

00:04:05.399 --> 00:04:08.759
what's something fun that you like to do in your free time as well,

00:04:08.839 --> 00:04:10.440
so we can get to know that side too?

00:04:11.479 --> 00:04:14.440
Well, one of them we probably already know.

00:04:14.440 --> 00:04:18.279
I'm a bit of a hobbyist with podcasting and general tech.

00:04:18.279 --> 00:04:21.720
But other than that, one that maybe people don't really know about

00:04:21.720 --> 00:04:23.160
is I grew up in Michigan.

00:04:23.160 --> 00:04:26.600
So I always grew up a sports fan, in particular, hockey.

00:04:26.600 --> 00:04:28.359
So I'm a big Detroit Red Wings fan,

00:04:28.359 --> 00:04:31.079
and they've had a little bit of a hard time the past few years.

00:04:31.079 --> 00:04:34.279
But in the 1990s, they were Stanley Cup champions,

00:04:34.279 --> 00:04:37.239
and those are some of the best years I've ever watched in sports.

00:04:37.399 --> 00:04:39.239
Certainly, I'm a big hockey fan, for sure.

00:04:40.200 --> 00:04:41.079
Nice.

00:04:41.079 --> 00:04:44.760
Well, I would love to get the conversation going around

00:04:44.760 --> 00:04:46.920
some of the community work that you do,

00:04:46.920 --> 00:04:49.799
because I'm always so impressed with all that you do.

00:04:50.359 --> 00:04:54.440
And I was just curious, how did you first get started in all this,

00:04:54.440 --> 00:04:59.559
and like podcasting and just getting involved with so many community events?

00:05:00.679 --> 00:05:03.959
Yeah, now it's going way back a ways,

00:05:03.959 --> 00:05:09.000
but the roots of this actually started in my dissertation back in grad school,

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:13.559
where I would not have been able to complete it without R,

00:05:13.559 --> 00:05:17.160
because R had the package from one of the leading authors

00:05:17.160 --> 00:05:21.399
of a manuscript for the method I was using called competing risk.

00:05:21.399 --> 00:05:23.559
And ever since that point,

00:05:23.559 --> 00:05:26.600
I not only used that package to crunch through the numbers,

00:05:26.600 --> 00:05:31.000
but then I was able to produce a dissertation with S-Weave,

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:35.720
which was a precursor to Knitter, and now what we know of R Markdown and Quarto.

00:05:35.720 --> 00:05:39.399
So I was hooked, like I thought R was amazing.

00:05:39.959 --> 00:05:42.600
I never really had training in it until then,

00:05:42.600 --> 00:05:46.279
so I was just enamored with the world of open source.

00:05:46.279 --> 00:05:50.679
And around this time, I was also getting into open source

00:05:50.679 --> 00:05:54.760
with respect to like the Linux operating system and things like that.

00:05:54.760 --> 00:05:59.720
And as I was learning things about Linux to help with my grad school duties,

00:06:00.440 --> 00:06:01.720
I found podcasts.

00:06:01.720 --> 00:06:06.519
There were some podcasters teaching me some great skills around Linux and open source,

00:06:06.519 --> 00:06:11.239
and really helped me in quite a few situations with some education there.

00:06:11.239 --> 00:06:15.640
And I thought, well, I like R so much, and I certainly don't know everything about it,

00:06:15.640 --> 00:06:19.720
but maybe if I just start to put myself out there a little bit

00:06:19.720 --> 00:06:23.799
and maybe see what might be receptive to people,

00:06:23.799 --> 00:06:26.920
and kind of like a little nudge to learn out loud

00:06:26.920 --> 00:06:29.640
before that became a catchphrase from Mara.

00:06:29.640 --> 00:06:34.920
So I started the R podcast back in 2012, 2011.

00:06:34.920 --> 00:06:39.959
I forgot the year, but it really just started me just kind of learning about R

00:06:39.959 --> 00:06:43.799
and a lot of the things that I hadn't had a chance to pursue yet.

00:06:43.799 --> 00:06:47.799
And lo and behold, I started to get some feedback that people were liking it,

00:06:48.359 --> 00:06:49.959
and I decided to keep going.

00:06:49.959 --> 00:06:53.160
And I think what really turned the corner on that

00:06:53.160 --> 00:06:56.279
was not just me doing my own learning,

00:06:56.279 --> 00:07:02.119
but to showcase the brilliant developers, package authors, practitioners

00:07:02.119 --> 00:07:03.880
that were doing amazing work.

00:07:03.880 --> 00:07:07.640
And I wanted to give them a platform to share their backstory,

00:07:07.640 --> 00:07:09.320
you know, how they got to where they were.

00:07:09.959 --> 00:07:13.640
And that started kind of my interview, you might say, sequence.

00:07:13.640 --> 00:07:18.679
And through those connections, just things happened organically after that.

00:07:18.679 --> 00:07:22.920
Started collaborating with NowPosit, formerly RStudio, quite a bit.

00:07:23.720 --> 00:07:26.359
Started to go to the various conferences and meetups.

00:07:26.359 --> 00:07:30.760
And lo and behold, I was learning so much from the community

00:07:31.320 --> 00:07:34.839
that it became a passion to keep that going.

00:07:34.839 --> 00:07:39.079
And then more recently, I decided to augment that into like Shiny

00:07:39.079 --> 00:07:41.239
because I'm so passionate about Shiny as well.

00:07:41.880 --> 00:07:44.600
Starting the Shiny Developer Series a couple of years ago.

00:07:44.600 --> 00:07:47.559
And now more recently, the R Weekly Project

00:07:47.559 --> 00:07:50.679
to help curate what is available in the community.

00:07:50.679 --> 00:07:53.720
So all these things just kind of happened organically.

00:07:53.720 --> 00:07:57.959
But I thought not many others are trying this route back in 2012

00:07:57.959 --> 00:08:00.279
to put themselves out there via voice.

00:08:00.279 --> 00:08:01.880
There are only a few blogs out there.

00:08:01.880 --> 00:08:05.640
But I thought if the Linux podcasters helped me so much,

00:08:06.200 --> 00:08:09.559
maybe I can help others in the R community too along the way.

00:08:09.559 --> 00:08:14.200
And like I said, learn for myself as well, but just share it with the world.

00:08:14.200 --> 00:08:17.079
So it all just kind of happened organically.

00:08:17.079 --> 00:08:18.679
And I'm glad I stuck with it.

00:08:18.679 --> 00:08:20.359
Certainly been off and on, as they say,

00:08:20.359 --> 00:08:25.079
but it's been a real, real passion of mine to share that knowledge.

00:08:25.079 --> 00:08:29.160
And like I said, to showcase who else is doing brilliant work in the community.

00:08:30.359 --> 00:08:31.000
That's great.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:33.960
And thank you so much for all that you do.

00:08:33.960 --> 00:08:37.080
I love that phrase, learning out loud

00:08:37.080 --> 00:08:40.359
and getting to see all the different examples through R Weekly too.

00:08:41.239 --> 00:08:45.880
Can I ask you, like thinking back to those early stages,

00:08:45.880 --> 00:08:48.200
what made you so enamored with open source?

00:08:49.640 --> 00:08:55.640
It was just the brilliant technology behind it.

00:08:55.640 --> 00:08:58.200
And the fact that we could get involved

00:08:58.200 --> 00:09:03.559
without having to jump through maybe a proprietary company to get there.

00:09:03.559 --> 00:09:05.239
That we could look at the source

00:09:05.239 --> 00:09:08.359
if we had questions about how to function worked.

00:09:08.359 --> 00:09:11.000
And for my dissertation, I had to look critically

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:13.080
at some of the methods I was using.

00:09:13.080 --> 00:09:17.479
So the fact that the package code was right there on CRAN at the time,

00:09:17.479 --> 00:09:19.479
I was able to look at the source,

00:09:19.479 --> 00:09:22.679
verify that this method was doing what I expected.

00:09:22.679 --> 00:09:24.359
But the fact that I could do that,

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:28.039
albeit it wasn't as easy as it is now with things like GitHub,

00:09:28.039 --> 00:09:29.640
but still I could get in there.

00:09:30.200 --> 00:09:33.479
I could read behind the lines, so to speak,

00:09:33.479 --> 00:09:35.000
try things out and experiment.

00:09:35.799 --> 00:09:38.679
And the fact that just so many innovations were happening

00:09:38.679 --> 00:09:40.440
in the general open source community

00:09:40.440 --> 00:09:44.119
that might take a big company years to get to.

00:09:44.119 --> 00:09:46.440
And at that point, I was just hooked.

00:09:46.440 --> 00:09:50.200
The fact that I could do this in statistical computing with R

00:09:50.200 --> 00:09:52.760
and then in my general grad school duties,

00:09:52.760 --> 00:09:55.960
be able to help others with pretty complicated projects,

00:09:55.960 --> 00:09:57.799
hooking R with different technology.

00:09:58.760 --> 00:10:02.359
It just was addicting to me that I could blend all this together

00:10:02.359 --> 00:10:05.640
without having to be a part of like a huge organization

00:10:05.640 --> 00:10:08.760
or sign a bunch of agreements to get access to things.

00:10:08.760 --> 00:10:11.479
It was just really a mind-blowing experience

00:10:11.479 --> 00:10:15.000
that I never really got wind of until I discovered R.

00:10:16.919 --> 00:10:18.039
That's great. Thank you.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:22.359
And I just wanted to remind everybody,

00:10:22.919 --> 00:10:24.840
I see a few questions coming in on Slido,

00:10:24.840 --> 00:10:27.239
but if you just joined a little bit into the session,

00:10:27.239 --> 00:10:30.280
you can ask questions through Slido anonymously

00:10:30.280 --> 00:10:33.000
and we'll share the link in the chat again here in a second.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:37.960
But you can also just jump in and raise your hand here on Zoom

00:10:37.960 --> 00:10:40.200
or put questions into the Zoom chat.

00:10:40.200 --> 00:10:43.799
But I see one of the anonymous question was,

00:10:43.799 --> 00:10:46.440
how have you married your love for R personally

00:10:46.440 --> 00:10:47.799
with your professional work?

00:10:49.479 --> 00:10:50.440
Great question.

00:10:50.440 --> 00:10:53.479
So this is another mini story time, as they say,

00:10:53.479 --> 00:10:57.320
but it was about a few years into my job

00:10:57.320 --> 00:10:58.760
where in the very beginning,

00:10:58.760 --> 00:11:00.679
I wasn't using R to do very much

00:11:00.679 --> 00:11:02.440
because I was assigned to do a more,

00:11:02.440 --> 00:11:06.840
you might say, traditional study project statistician role

00:11:06.840 --> 00:11:09.479
where I was helping oversee the analysis strategy

00:11:09.479 --> 00:11:10.599
of a particular study.

00:11:11.320 --> 00:11:13.799
And as many might know in life sciences,

00:11:13.799 --> 00:11:17.320
SAS has been the predominant player in computation there,

00:11:17.320 --> 00:11:20.359
but that's slowly changing, which we may get to later.

00:11:20.359 --> 00:11:25.000
But over time, they hooked me into an assignment,

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:26.760
pretty open-ended assignment,

00:11:26.760 --> 00:11:29.239
where you're getting a lot of complicated biomarker data.

00:11:29.799 --> 00:11:31.640
And this data was huge.

00:11:31.640 --> 00:11:32.679
And we were trying to use

00:11:32.679 --> 00:11:35.239
some pretty novel algorithms with it.

00:11:35.239 --> 00:11:36.760
And that's where R came into play.

00:11:36.760 --> 00:11:39.799
I was finally able to take what I learned in my dissertation

00:11:39.799 --> 00:11:43.320
and start applying to actual work at the day job.

00:11:43.320 --> 00:11:44.440
And then along the way,

00:11:45.080 --> 00:11:46.919
we had another talented colleague

00:11:46.919 --> 00:11:48.520
that was running at that time

00:11:48.520 --> 00:11:51.640
called the SNR user group at Lilly.

00:11:52.200 --> 00:11:55.080
And I started calling into it much like a hangout here,

00:11:55.080 --> 00:11:57.559
but it was just people sharing what they were doing,

00:11:57.559 --> 00:11:59.159
small but enthusiastic group.

00:11:59.159 --> 00:12:02.919
And then within maybe a year or so of me attending that,

00:12:02.919 --> 00:12:04.679
the leader of this group said,

00:12:04.679 --> 00:12:05.960
hey, Eric, you know what?

00:12:05.960 --> 00:12:07.960
I think you should take the reins on this.

00:12:07.960 --> 00:12:09.320
And at first I'm kind of shocked

00:12:09.320 --> 00:12:11.799
because I've only been with the company for a couple of years.

00:12:11.799 --> 00:12:14.840
And this great colleague was very well respected

00:12:14.840 --> 00:12:15.799
for asking me to do this.

00:12:15.799 --> 00:12:18.440
But ever since then, that's when I thought,

00:12:18.440 --> 00:12:21.239
okay, now it's time to take this to another level.

00:12:21.239 --> 00:12:23.799
And lo and behold, I've been leading the internal R group

00:12:23.799 --> 00:12:27.159
for about, yeah, eight, nine years.

00:12:27.159 --> 00:12:31.320
And that's been another tremendous asset to my learning

00:12:31.880 --> 00:12:33.320
and also getting insights

00:12:33.320 --> 00:12:36.359
to what others in the organization are doing with R.

00:12:36.359 --> 00:12:38.119
Because sometimes people might think,

00:12:38.119 --> 00:12:39.400
oh, this contribution,

00:12:39.400 --> 00:12:40.919
yeah, I just did a little bit here and there,

00:12:40.919 --> 00:12:43.080
but I'm like, no, you should highlight that.

00:12:43.080 --> 00:12:44.840
Let me give you a platform to share that

00:12:44.840 --> 00:12:47.479
because we can all learn from your experience.

00:12:47.479 --> 00:12:51.000
And then we'll all be sharing that knowledge together.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:53.400
So definitely helping with that user group

00:12:53.400 --> 00:12:54.520
has been a big help.

00:12:54.520 --> 00:12:57.239
And just that little nudge to do something

00:12:57.239 --> 00:12:59.960
a little outside the box early in my career

00:13:00.520 --> 00:13:04.039
gave me that little, I'd say, nudge to take this further.

00:13:04.039 --> 00:13:06.280
So again, kind of an organic thing,

00:13:06.280 --> 00:13:08.919
but I'm very happy it happened that way

00:13:08.919 --> 00:13:11.080
because it definitely changed a lot of things

00:13:11.080 --> 00:13:11.960
for the better for me.

00:13:12.799 --> 00:13:14.440
Awesome.

00:13:14.440 --> 00:13:16.119
I'm starting to see a lot of questions

00:13:16.119 --> 00:13:17.640
coming in here in the chat too.

00:13:17.640 --> 00:13:19.159
I see Libby just asked one.

00:13:19.159 --> 00:13:19.880
Do you want to jump in?

00:13:22.440 --> 00:13:22.919
Sure.

00:13:22.919 --> 00:13:24.840
I was wondering if you always knew

00:13:24.840 --> 00:13:28.359
that you would go to industry after your PhD

00:13:28.359 --> 00:13:30.359
or if you contemplated staying in academia?

00:13:31.719 --> 00:13:32.919
Yeah, excellent question.

00:13:33.479 --> 00:13:35.080
And first, Libby, congratulations

00:13:35.080 --> 00:13:36.520
from one podcaster to another.

00:13:36.520 --> 00:13:37.640
So I had to shout that out.

00:13:39.640 --> 00:13:42.679
I did have a pretty inkling early on

00:13:42.679 --> 00:13:45.640
that if I was going to, after I started to decide

00:13:45.640 --> 00:13:48.359
to do the PhD, which actually was not instantaneous,

00:13:48.359 --> 00:13:50.679
I thought I was just going to get a master's degree

00:13:50.679 --> 00:13:51.400
and be done with it.

00:13:51.400 --> 00:13:54.840
But I had a few people that were very close to me say,

00:13:54.840 --> 00:13:55.960
if you're going to get the PhD,

00:13:55.960 --> 00:13:57.080
you might want to do it now

00:13:57.080 --> 00:13:59.640
before things get kind of crazy later in life.

00:13:59.640 --> 00:14:01.880
But then as I'm going through that,

00:14:01.880 --> 00:14:04.760
I do admit what I heard from other colleagues,

00:14:04.760 --> 00:14:08.200
those that graduated in the same program years prior

00:14:08.200 --> 00:14:11.320
were really enjoying the experience being in industry,

00:14:11.320 --> 00:14:15.479
whether it was life sciences or other sectors in the world.

00:14:15.479 --> 00:14:16.760
And I thought, you know what?

00:14:16.760 --> 00:14:19.000
Yeah, I want to make a difference.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:20.280
And I felt like at that time,

00:14:20.280 --> 00:14:22.520
that would be the easiest way to do it.

00:14:22.520 --> 00:14:26.119
But again, I have other great colleagues in academia.

00:14:26.119 --> 00:14:28.599
So everybody's got their own preferences.

00:14:28.599 --> 00:14:30.200
But I kind of knew pretty early on

00:14:30.200 --> 00:14:32.679
that it was going to be an industry-type role for me.

00:14:32.679 --> 00:14:34.520
And I've been happy with it ever since.

00:14:35.320 --> 00:14:36.599
Awesome, thank you.

00:14:36.599 --> 00:14:37.099
You bet.

00:14:38.359 --> 00:14:39.640
Eric, you just said,

00:14:39.640 --> 00:14:42.919
we're probably going to get a few SAS questions coming in.

00:14:42.919 --> 00:14:45.159
And we have a few on Slido for you.

00:14:45.719 --> 00:14:49.239
One was, how have you convinced leadership in pharma

00:14:49.239 --> 00:14:52.200
to move away from proprietary programming languages

00:14:52.200 --> 00:14:56.760
like SAS over to open source languages like R or Python?

00:14:57.960 --> 00:14:59.719
Yeah, well, that's a good thing.

00:14:59.719 --> 00:15:01.080
We got some time for this,

00:15:01.080 --> 00:15:02.919
but I can keep this kind of brief to start.

00:15:02.919 --> 00:15:07.640
But it was kind of leading by example a little bit.

00:15:07.640 --> 00:15:11.479
I think that to solve complicated issues,

00:15:11.479 --> 00:15:12.599
especially what I was doing

00:15:12.599 --> 00:15:15.960
in that early assignment with biomarker analysis,

00:15:15.960 --> 00:15:17.400
I wanted to demonstrate

00:15:17.400 --> 00:15:20.200
that the outputs I can get from this,

00:15:20.200 --> 00:15:22.440
the analytics I can run from this,

00:15:23.080 --> 00:15:25.159
and do it efficiently to tie in

00:15:25.159 --> 00:15:28.359
to some really important HPC,

00:15:28.359 --> 00:15:30.280
high-performance computing infrastructure,

00:15:30.359 --> 00:15:34.359
which at that time was not very easy to do in the SAS world.

00:15:34.359 --> 00:15:37.000
I was able to turn around answers pretty quickly

00:15:37.559 --> 00:15:40.039
and be able to share insights with the leadership,

00:15:40.039 --> 00:15:41.559
the clinical team.

00:15:42.280 --> 00:15:43.320
And they were saying,

00:15:43.320 --> 00:15:44.359
hey, this is great.

00:15:44.359 --> 00:15:46.280
Keep going, keep going with it.

00:15:46.280 --> 00:15:47.960
So leading by example.

00:15:47.960 --> 00:15:50.200
And then honestly, the other key event

00:15:50.200 --> 00:15:52.200
that's happening across our industry

00:15:53.080 --> 00:15:56.840
is the invent of the now the fourth

00:15:56.840 --> 00:15:59.799
or fifth year running our pharma conference,

00:15:59.880 --> 00:16:02.599
where now many of us that are passionate

00:16:02.599 --> 00:16:04.760
about using R in the clinical realm

00:16:05.320 --> 00:16:08.599
got together, organized this event from the ground up.

00:16:09.239 --> 00:16:12.280
Maybe we have some of them listening here on the chat here.

00:16:12.280 --> 00:16:14.599
But that really started to open eyes

00:16:14.599 --> 00:16:18.919
of many of the industry leaders and life sciences to say,

00:16:18.919 --> 00:16:21.239
hey, look what these people are doing with open source.

00:16:21.239 --> 00:16:23.479
Look how they're bringing automation

00:16:23.479 --> 00:16:25.479
in a seamless way with integrating R

00:16:25.479 --> 00:16:27.159
with other pipelines

00:16:27.159 --> 00:16:29.320
and generating interactive insights.

00:16:29.400 --> 00:16:33.080
And it's just really grown exponentially since then.

00:16:33.080 --> 00:16:34.919
And a lot of this is not possible

00:16:34.919 --> 00:16:37.719
without the open source nature of R,

00:16:37.719 --> 00:16:39.799
what we can grab from the community,

00:16:39.799 --> 00:16:42.840
but also integrate it with other systems really easily.

00:16:42.840 --> 00:16:46.119
Whether it's databases, high performance computing,

00:16:46.119 --> 00:16:48.119
obviously shiny for web applications.

00:16:48.119 --> 00:16:50.440
There's so many integrations that are possible

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:54.919
that other proprietary packages may have some solutions for.

00:16:55.479 --> 00:16:57.000
But A, they cost money.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:59.000
B, they can cost a lot of time.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:00.840
But if you build up the talent,

00:17:00.840 --> 00:17:05.000
you can do amazing things with R and the other integrations.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:06.920
And I'm not going to sugarcoat it.

00:17:06.920 --> 00:17:09.239
We're still not quite where I want to get to yet,

00:17:09.239 --> 00:17:12.439
but we're definitely a lot farther in the last few years

00:17:12.439 --> 00:17:15.479
than we ever were when I started working in life sciences.

00:17:16.760 --> 00:17:18.280
Thank you.

00:17:20.199 --> 00:17:22.760
Kind of along those lines, another question was,

00:17:22.760 --> 00:17:25.560
do you have any suggestions for beginners

00:17:25.560 --> 00:17:28.520
who had experience in SAS but are new to R?

00:17:28.520 --> 00:17:31.479
Are there any specific approaches for better results?

00:17:33.719 --> 00:17:35.800
OK, well, time for some hot takes perhaps.

00:17:36.439 --> 00:17:38.920
So like that question probably insinuates,

00:17:38.920 --> 00:17:40.280
I also started with SAS.

00:17:40.280 --> 00:17:42.599
I did not know R before SAS.

00:17:42.599 --> 00:17:44.839
They are fundamentally different.

00:17:44.839 --> 00:17:47.239
So honestly, the first thing to keep in mind

00:17:47.239 --> 00:17:51.160
is that many of the practices or maybe tricks

00:17:51.160 --> 00:17:53.239
you've learned about how to do things in SAS,

00:17:53.959 --> 00:17:55.880
probably not going to work with R.

00:17:55.880 --> 00:17:59.160
They are fundamentally different from a language perspective.

00:17:59.160 --> 00:18:02.359
So you've got to check that to the side a little bit

00:18:02.359 --> 00:18:03.880
and go in with an open mind.

00:18:04.520 --> 00:18:06.599
It will be challenging at first, but I'm

00:18:06.599 --> 00:18:08.839
going to echo what others in the community have said,

00:18:08.839 --> 00:18:12.760
is that I would say getting started with the tidyverse,

00:18:12.760 --> 00:18:16.119
that's going to be pretty familiar in the way

00:18:16.119 --> 00:18:18.839
the pipe works and other things like that with dplyr

00:18:18.839 --> 00:18:22.119
and the like to what you might do in the SAS data

00:18:22.119 --> 00:18:23.479
step historically.

00:18:23.479 --> 00:18:26.920
So I think the tidyverse eases that transition a little bit,

00:18:26.920 --> 00:18:28.920
but there are going to be some habits that you'll

00:18:28.920 --> 00:18:30.599
have to grow into.

00:18:30.599 --> 00:18:34.359
But I think that the materials online are really

00:18:34.359 --> 00:18:35.880
great to get started with this.

00:18:35.880 --> 00:18:39.160
In fact, Minae's Data Science in a Box

00:18:39.160 --> 00:18:41.000
is another excellent resource, I think,

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:43.880
to get started with that we can probably link to.

00:18:43.880 --> 00:18:47.000
There's lots of educational materials out there,

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:51.640
but unlearn the old habits first before you dive into it.

00:18:51.640 --> 00:18:53.000
That would be my biggest advice.

00:18:54.479 --> 00:18:56.199
Thank you.

00:18:56.199 --> 00:18:59.239
I just copied over the Data Science in a Box

00:18:59.239 --> 00:19:00.280
over to the chat, too.

00:19:01.880 --> 00:19:05.079
I see, Javier, you had asked a question in the Zoom chat.

00:19:05.079 --> 00:19:06.119
Do you want to jump in next?

00:19:10.280 --> 00:19:11.400
Thanks, Rachel.

00:19:11.400 --> 00:19:13.479
And Eric, huge fan of yours.

00:19:13.479 --> 00:19:15.079
I feel a little starstruck here.

00:19:15.079 --> 00:19:17.719
Like I've been following your podcast for years,

00:19:17.719 --> 00:19:20.520
and I can't believe I just recently discovered

00:19:20.520 --> 00:19:21.959
the Shiny Developer Series.

00:19:21.959 --> 00:19:23.719
So seriously, thank you for everything

00:19:23.719 --> 00:19:27.239
you're throwing back into the ether here.

00:19:29.319 --> 00:19:34.040
Yeah, I have always worked for mostly large companies.

00:19:34.040 --> 00:19:39.719
And when I got into my first real data science role,

00:19:41.400 --> 00:19:47.800
I noticed that a lot of the Excel cleanup tasks

00:19:47.800 --> 00:19:51.560
or just a lot of the mundane repetitive tasks

00:19:51.560 --> 00:19:56.199
that so many people are doing on a weekly or monthly

00:19:56.199 --> 00:19:59.640
or quarterly basis, it should be automated.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:04.599
Sometimes they are just so disconnected from data science,

00:20:04.599 --> 00:20:08.439
they have no advocate or no teacher,

00:20:08.439 --> 00:20:12.040
no friend to be like, there are better ways

00:20:12.040 --> 00:20:13.319
of doing what you are doing.

00:20:15.319 --> 00:20:17.079
I also come from a finance background,

00:20:17.079 --> 00:20:19.160
so I'm sort of nuanced.

00:20:19.160 --> 00:20:20.760
My experiences are nuanced in that way.

00:20:20.760 --> 00:20:26.680
But have you had any experience trying to advocate

00:20:26.680 --> 00:20:31.079
for R or Closet Connect or Shiny and trying

00:20:31.079 --> 00:20:35.800
to educate these different teams in corporate finance,

00:20:35.800 --> 00:20:39.800
accounting, tax, or different reporting teams

00:20:39.800 --> 00:20:45.239
and try to get them to use some of the R tool stack?

00:20:45.239 --> 00:20:46.199
Is that Eli Lilly?

00:20:47.800 --> 00:20:49.160
Yeah, excellent question.

00:20:49.239 --> 00:20:51.160
And first of all, thank you for your very kind words.

00:20:51.160 --> 00:20:53.319
It's great to see that some of these little endeavors

00:20:53.319 --> 00:20:54.439
have a positive impact.

00:20:54.439 --> 00:20:55.560
That's always gratifying.

00:20:56.520 --> 00:21:00.199
I would say that in my early part of the career,

00:21:01.640 --> 00:21:05.079
I've been pretty fortunate that a lot of the leadership

00:21:05.079 --> 00:21:08.599
that's kind of been more close to me have seen the value

00:21:08.599 --> 00:21:11.479
of what I was bringing and be able to let me take

00:21:11.479 --> 00:21:14.760
what I'll call calculated risk to make that happen.

00:21:14.760 --> 00:21:20.599
And in fact, one of those was way back in probably 2011 or so

00:21:21.319 --> 00:21:24.839
when RStudio first, not closet, first released

00:21:25.479 --> 00:21:26.920
the RStudio server.

00:21:27.640 --> 00:21:31.880
I worked with our research IT group to get me

00:21:31.880 --> 00:21:34.839
a virtual machine that I had root access to,

00:21:34.839 --> 00:21:37.479
and they let me throw RStudio server on there

00:21:37.479 --> 00:21:38.760
because I thought at the time,

00:21:38.760 --> 00:21:41.800
after playing with that at home on my Linux systems,

00:21:41.800 --> 00:21:43.640
because I have a bit of a Linux geek here,

00:21:43.719 --> 00:21:47.079
that, hey, this could change the way we develop this at Lilly.

00:21:47.800 --> 00:21:51.880
And I'm very fortunate that the IT group didn't say like,

00:21:51.880 --> 00:21:55.160
oh, this new young statistician wants to do what?

00:21:55.160 --> 00:21:56.280
We don't let them do that.

00:21:56.280 --> 00:21:56.680
No, no, no.

00:21:56.680 --> 00:21:57.880
They were complete opposite.

00:21:57.880 --> 00:22:00.520
They said, hey, we're going to give you a little training

00:22:00.520 --> 00:22:03.079
on this, but we're going to leave it to you.

00:22:03.079 --> 00:22:05.880
And lo and behold, I got people hooked on developing

00:22:05.880 --> 00:22:08.119
R code efficiently on that server.

00:22:08.119 --> 00:22:10.359
Then Shiny server came along and I did basically

00:22:10.359 --> 00:22:11.239
the same thing then.

00:22:11.719 --> 00:22:14.439
And that's when people started to put little Shiny apps

00:22:14.439 --> 00:22:17.000
that were doing maybe very little in the beginning,

00:22:17.560 --> 00:22:20.520
but it opened the eyes of leadership

00:22:20.520 --> 00:22:23.640
when they could quickly do an interactive visualization

00:22:23.640 --> 00:22:27.239
of a trial result or maybe a custom data set.

00:22:27.239 --> 00:22:29.079
And so that leading by example,

00:22:29.079 --> 00:22:31.160
started to get the attention of leadership.

00:22:31.160 --> 00:22:34.439
And then over time, my role kind of morphed

00:22:34.439 --> 00:22:37.959
into being this hybrid of a statistician

00:22:37.959 --> 00:22:40.599
and you might say an engineer kind of combining

00:22:40.599 --> 00:22:45.079
the best of both so that I could execute on these ideas.

00:22:45.079 --> 00:22:47.239
And again, be given the freedom

00:22:47.239 --> 00:22:48.599
to try some of these things out.

00:22:49.319 --> 00:22:51.000
Has everything I've done worked?

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:52.199
Not everything.

00:22:52.199 --> 00:22:54.119
There've been a couple of dead ends here and there,

00:22:54.119 --> 00:22:56.760
but I've been fortunate that the leadership

00:22:56.760 --> 00:22:59.640
are ready to embrace an idea of saving time,

00:23:00.199 --> 00:23:03.640
saving money, and the fact that I could automate

00:23:03.640 --> 00:23:07.239
the creation of maybe a hundred biomarkers

00:23:07.239 --> 00:23:09.400
being summarized in one Shiny app

00:23:09.400 --> 00:23:14.119
versus an RTF output printing a hundred pages per marker.

00:23:14.680 --> 00:23:17.560
That got attention, just that little win right there.

00:23:17.560 --> 00:23:19.400
So it started small.

00:23:19.400 --> 00:23:21.640
I didn't start big, so to speak,

00:23:21.640 --> 00:23:23.560
but it started with incremental things.

00:23:24.119 --> 00:23:25.880
And then it got to the point where people

00:23:25.880 --> 00:23:28.599
were seeking me out to help with advice

00:23:28.599 --> 00:23:30.599
on how they can automate something with R

00:23:30.599 --> 00:23:34.760
or maybe in combo with Shiny or other utilities

00:23:34.760 --> 00:23:38.760
instead of them settling for a default manual process.

00:23:38.760 --> 00:23:40.760
But it didn't, it wasn't overnight.

00:23:40.760 --> 00:23:43.400
It was incremental kind of wins along the way.

00:23:45.920 --> 00:23:47.319
Thank you.

00:23:48.599 --> 00:23:51.800
So I see a question over on Slido.

00:23:51.800 --> 00:23:53.319
And Andy, I see your name there.

00:23:53.319 --> 00:23:54.359
So feel free to jump in

00:23:54.359 --> 00:23:56.680
if you want to add any other context too.

00:23:57.319 --> 00:23:58.520
They can ask it.

00:23:58.520 --> 00:24:01.479
It's what can you share regarding building

00:24:01.479 --> 00:24:04.040
a community of practice in a larger org

00:24:04.040 --> 00:24:06.040
in terms of finding other R users

00:24:06.040 --> 00:24:08.520
and growing and sustaining interest?

00:24:09.319 --> 00:24:11.880
Yeah, this is certainly another,

00:24:11.880 --> 00:24:13.719
you know, I say passion area of mine

00:24:13.719 --> 00:24:16.280
because I've, as I said, kind of in the outset,

00:24:16.280 --> 00:24:18.359
the idea of bringing people together

00:24:18.359 --> 00:24:19.880
and sharing knowledge has been something

00:24:19.880 --> 00:24:21.560
I've been excited about for a long time.

00:24:22.439 --> 00:24:25.000
It's not always easy because again,

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:27.239
we have to sometimes fight a little stigma

00:24:27.239 --> 00:24:30.119
amongst ourselves that we feel like

00:24:30.119 --> 00:24:32.359
the things we're doing with either R

00:24:32.359 --> 00:24:34.920
or just in general what we're doing with analytics

00:24:34.920 --> 00:24:36.520
isn't really that innovative.

00:24:36.520 --> 00:24:38.280
It's just like part of the job, so to speak.

00:24:38.359 --> 00:24:40.599
But I'm trying to get people to come

00:24:40.599 --> 00:24:41.800
out of their shell a little bit

00:24:41.800 --> 00:24:45.000
and celebrate it and not feel like everything

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:48.040
has to be super polished before they show it to us.

00:24:48.599 --> 00:24:50.359
I really made a concerted effort

00:24:50.359 --> 00:24:52.520
in the last few years to say,

00:24:52.520 --> 00:24:55.640
hey, we are a welcoming group.

00:24:55.640 --> 00:24:57.719
We would love to share our ideas.

00:24:57.719 --> 00:25:00.199
If you want advice, we're happy to give it.

00:25:00.199 --> 00:25:02.359
If you have any stumbling blocks,

00:25:02.359 --> 00:25:04.119
we're happy to help solve it.

00:25:04.119 --> 00:25:06.119
But even if you just found a great package

00:25:06.119 --> 00:25:07.640
that simplified your workflow,

00:25:08.680 --> 00:25:10.280
we just want to know about it.

00:25:10.280 --> 00:25:12.359
It doesn't have to be anything fancy.

00:25:12.359 --> 00:25:15.160
So making sure people felt comfortable

00:25:15.160 --> 00:25:17.000
that sharing any contribution,

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:18.599
no matter quote, big or small,

00:25:19.239 --> 00:25:21.719
has been one of the things we've really tried to do.

00:25:22.280 --> 00:25:25.560
And honestly, finding a diverse set of topics

00:25:25.560 --> 00:25:26.599
that we can learn from,

00:25:26.599 --> 00:25:29.239
because not everybody is going to be interested

00:25:29.239 --> 00:25:31.079
in the things I'm interested in, right?

00:25:31.079 --> 00:25:34.359
But finding others to kind of give a different voice,

00:25:34.359 --> 00:25:35.560
a different perspective,

00:25:35.560 --> 00:25:37.239
whether it's from, you know,

00:25:37.239 --> 00:25:39.560
creating that great table with GT

00:25:39.560 --> 00:25:41.959
or automating a pipeline with,

00:25:41.959 --> 00:25:44.359
you know, connecting R with AWS,

00:25:44.359 --> 00:25:46.439
you know, lots of different things are out there

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:49.239
and making sure that there's a protected time

00:25:49.239 --> 00:25:50.839
for people to showcase that.

00:25:51.479 --> 00:25:54.439
Having a regular cadence has always been helpful too.

00:25:54.439 --> 00:25:56.520
But I'll admit I'm not the best at it,

00:25:56.520 --> 00:25:59.640
but I try to surround myself with others

00:25:59.640 --> 00:26:01.880
that are enthusiastic about the same things,

00:26:01.880 --> 00:26:03.800
the building this community.

00:26:03.800 --> 00:26:06.599
So not doing it alone is definitely one piece of advice.

00:26:06.599 --> 00:26:10.119
Find somebody else to tag along and help along the way.

00:26:11.400 --> 00:26:12.920
I certainly appreciate that, Eric.

00:26:12.920 --> 00:26:13.420
Thank you.

00:26:14.119 --> 00:26:17.400
A couple of things I really got from what you just said,

00:26:17.400 --> 00:26:20.680
the piece we're not doing alone,

00:26:20.680 --> 00:26:23.400
I'm certainly on track for that.

00:26:23.400 --> 00:26:24.520
I work in public health

00:26:24.520 --> 00:26:27.160
at a large public state public health agency.

00:26:27.880 --> 00:26:33.160
And there was an R user group a couple of years ago

00:26:33.160 --> 00:26:35.000
before I came to the agency.

00:26:35.880 --> 00:26:38.119
And that, I guess, sort of fizzled out.

00:26:38.119 --> 00:26:40.599
And now there's more interest in it.

00:26:40.599 --> 00:26:42.839
And so I've connected with the person

00:26:42.839 --> 00:26:47.239
who had kind of started organizing the group previously.

00:26:47.239 --> 00:26:49.479
And so we're going to work together

00:26:50.119 --> 00:26:53.719
and try to reach a wider,

00:26:55.479 --> 00:26:58.119
cast a wider net within the organization as well.

00:26:58.119 --> 00:27:00.520
And then, and I love the piece

00:27:00.520 --> 00:27:03.400
about really encouraging the small shares.

00:27:03.400 --> 00:27:06.520
And even in the safe space,

00:27:06.520 --> 00:27:09.640
we're certainly folding in that our agency

00:27:09.640 --> 00:27:12.839
has both internally facing

00:27:12.839 --> 00:27:16.199
and externally facing equity goals.

00:27:16.199 --> 00:27:23.239
And so we're folding all that into our agreements

00:27:23.239 --> 00:27:28.520
with how we meet and work with each other.

00:27:29.479 --> 00:27:30.920
So I appreciate that as well

00:27:30.920 --> 00:27:33.959
about the inclusiveness forefront of that.

00:27:33.959 --> 00:27:34.839
So thank you.

00:27:34.839 --> 00:27:36.520
Oh, my pleasure.

00:27:36.520 --> 00:27:39.160
And those things, as long as you start with those,

00:27:39.160 --> 00:27:40.680
everything else is going to fall in place.

00:27:40.680 --> 00:27:42.680
Like it may not always be easy,

00:27:42.680 --> 00:27:45.959
but if you set those expectations,

00:27:45.959 --> 00:27:47.800
set that safe space,

