But jumping over to a few other questions,

00:29:26.760 --> 00:29:30.520
I see there was one on Slido, Eric,

00:29:30.520 --> 00:29:32.280
that was, does the data science team

00:29:32.280 --> 00:29:35.560
ever have trouble getting resources from the IT team?

00:29:35.560 --> 00:29:37.400
If so, how do you navigate that?

00:29:39.239 --> 00:29:39.880
Oh yeah.

00:29:39.880 --> 00:29:41.640
Okay, another hot topic for me.

00:29:43.239 --> 00:29:45.719
What there, it's been a mix of both, I'll say.

00:29:46.520 --> 00:29:48.920
What helped me early in my career

00:29:48.920 --> 00:29:52.040
as making great relationships

00:29:52.040 --> 00:29:53.880
with that same research IT group

00:29:53.880 --> 00:29:55.400
that gave me the keys, so to speak,

00:29:55.400 --> 00:29:56.680
to that virtual server,

00:29:57.239 --> 00:29:59.319
that has grown into probably

00:29:59.319 --> 00:30:02.839
my most valuable collaboration in the entire company.

00:30:03.560 --> 00:30:04.920
I'm probably sounding strong with that,

00:30:04.920 --> 00:30:05.719
but it really is.

00:30:06.439 --> 00:30:08.760
They have helped us out immensely

00:30:08.760 --> 00:30:11.959
with infrastructure, with our HPC needs,

00:30:11.959 --> 00:30:13.400
and really pushing the envelope

00:30:13.400 --> 00:30:16.119
what we can do with R inside the enterprise.

00:30:16.680 --> 00:30:17.959
And how I got there,

00:30:17.959 --> 00:30:19.800
this is a fun little, you might say,

00:30:19.800 --> 00:30:22.680
data mishaps story that I shared earlier this year

00:30:22.680 --> 00:30:24.280
at a data mishaps conference.

00:30:24.280 --> 00:30:26.680
But I just so happened in my eagerness

00:30:26.680 --> 00:30:29.719
to turn loose on this really complicated analysis

00:30:29.719 --> 00:30:32.680
to bring down the entire HPC cluster one day.

00:30:32.680 --> 00:30:33.880
Like I brought it down.

00:30:33.880 --> 00:30:36.199
It went crash into a halt.

00:30:36.199 --> 00:30:38.439
And you can imagine the panic I felt

00:30:38.439 --> 00:30:40.680
being a new statistician doing something like that.

00:30:40.680 --> 00:30:42.680
But this IT group didn't say,

00:30:42.680 --> 00:30:43.880
okay, we're not going to give him

00:30:43.880 --> 00:30:45.880
any capabilities of doing this anymore.

00:30:45.880 --> 00:30:47.479
They took me under their wing

00:30:47.479 --> 00:30:49.160
and they really educated me

00:30:49.160 --> 00:30:51.560
on what I could do better next time.

00:30:51.560 --> 00:30:53.160
But they said, we want to partner with you.

00:30:53.160 --> 00:30:55.000
We know you've got the ambition

00:30:55.000 --> 00:30:57.880
to really utilize the tech in the best way.

00:30:57.880 --> 00:30:59.800
And we want to bring you under our wing.

00:30:59.800 --> 00:31:01.880
And that's been really fruitful.

00:31:01.880 --> 00:31:03.719
So whenever I need anything from them

00:31:03.719 --> 00:31:04.920
or they need anything from me,

00:31:04.920 --> 00:31:07.079
we're there for each other.

00:31:07.079 --> 00:31:10.199
It's not always that way in other parts of the IT world.

00:31:10.199 --> 00:31:12.760
So it does pay to build those relationships

00:31:12.760 --> 00:31:14.920
with those that maybe kind of get

00:31:14.920 --> 00:31:16.040
where you're trying to get to

00:31:16.040 --> 00:31:19.000
and they can help translate some of the processes

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:21.319
or some of the hoops you have to jump through.

00:31:21.319 --> 00:31:24.599
So I've been trying to keep those going fruitfully.

00:31:25.239 --> 00:31:27.160
And then it's really just being persistent

00:31:27.160 --> 00:31:30.680
and showing why you need that certain access key

00:31:30.680 --> 00:31:33.959
or why you need access to that API.

00:31:33.959 --> 00:31:36.439
Really just showing them what you're trying to do here.

00:31:36.439 --> 00:31:37.319
And I've been fortunate.

00:31:37.319 --> 00:31:39.239
Once they see the value of it,

00:31:39.239 --> 00:31:41.239
they're going to go to bat for me to get it.

00:31:41.239 --> 00:31:42.760
It just sometimes can take a while

00:31:42.760 --> 00:31:45.319
because there are many different IT groups

00:31:45.319 --> 00:31:48.520
across security, DevOps, and all the other sectors

00:31:48.520 --> 00:31:50.119
that you have to navigate through.

00:31:50.119 --> 00:31:52.680
But with the strong relationships,

00:31:52.680 --> 00:31:54.280
that can become easier.

00:31:56.040 --> 00:31:58.359
I love to see all the chat

00:31:58.359 --> 00:32:00.680
that's happening during the Hangout too.

00:32:02.280 --> 00:32:03.000
Thank you, Eric.

