00:32:21.880 --> 00:32:24.760
and joining in all the great conversations.

00:32:24.760 --> 00:32:26.359
And I've been looking forward

00:32:26.359 --> 00:32:27.719
to the conversation with Eric

00:32:27.719 --> 00:32:30.920
because the domain I'm in, in pharma and insurance.

00:32:30.920 --> 00:32:33.479
So I have had similar experiences

00:32:33.479 --> 00:32:36.359
of incremental building out solutions

00:32:36.359 --> 00:32:40.040
and then having them be adopted in the org.

00:32:40.040 --> 00:32:42.439
So I have a lot of questions,

00:32:42.439 --> 00:32:43.640
but I would just keep it short.

00:32:43.640 --> 00:32:45.560
Maybe two questions for now.

00:32:45.560 --> 00:32:46.599
One would be like,

00:32:46.599 --> 00:32:49.400
how do you facilitate your SAS programmers

00:32:49.400 --> 00:32:53.400
to learn R or get into the R ecosystem

00:32:53.400 --> 00:32:55.560
and be open to it?

00:32:55.560 --> 00:32:56.680
Because in my experience,

00:32:56.680 --> 00:32:58.920
what I've understood is SAS programmers

00:32:58.920 --> 00:33:01.319
try to be in that tech or domain

00:33:01.319 --> 00:33:03.160
because of the stability and everything around it.

00:33:03.880 --> 00:33:07.000
And plus, since RStudio rebranded to Post-it

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:09.239
and how they have launched Shiny for Python

00:33:09.239 --> 00:33:12.040
and serverless Shiny applications,

00:33:12.040 --> 00:33:16.119
you being a Shiny trainer yourself,

00:33:16.119 --> 00:33:17.479
what are your thoughts around it?

00:33:17.479 --> 00:33:19.719
And how do you see the adaptability

00:33:19.719 --> 00:33:23.000
of Shiny for Python in pharma industry assets?

00:33:24.479 --> 00:33:26.439
Yeah, great questions.

00:33:26.439 --> 00:33:27.640
Thank you for those.

00:33:27.640 --> 00:33:28.839
So with the first one,

00:33:29.560 --> 00:33:31.000
what has helped us,

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:32.280
and I will admit, again,

00:33:32.280 --> 00:33:35.160
we can go much farther than we're currently at,

00:33:35.160 --> 00:33:37.000
but one of the wins that we've had

00:33:37.560 --> 00:33:40.520
is trying to look at the big strengths of R

00:33:40.520 --> 00:33:42.520
in certain situations

00:33:42.520 --> 00:33:44.680
and just let things kind of grow from there.

00:33:44.680 --> 00:33:47.160
So one example is that we've been embracing

00:33:47.800 --> 00:33:51.079
quite a bit the idea of interactive R Markdown reports.

00:33:51.079 --> 00:33:54.119
And now interactive portal is becoming a huge thing

00:33:54.119 --> 00:33:55.319
that we got our attention on,

00:33:55.319 --> 00:33:58.280
but showing our traditional,

00:33:58.280 --> 00:34:01.319
you might say, SAS analyst group that,

00:34:01.319 --> 00:34:02.599
hey, with a little investment

00:34:02.599 --> 00:34:04.280
in learning how R Markdown works,

00:34:04.280 --> 00:34:08.600
we can give you this interactive plot of efficacy results

00:34:08.600 --> 00:34:10.120
using something like Plotly

00:34:10.120 --> 00:34:12.040
and be able to quickly drill down

00:34:12.679 --> 00:34:15.000
and zoom in on certain data insights

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:16.760
from that visualization

00:34:16.760 --> 00:34:18.840
that you would have to produce like 10,

00:34:18.840 --> 00:34:20.679
12 plots individually

00:34:20.679 --> 00:34:23.320
to get to that same result in a static way.

00:34:23.320 --> 00:34:26.199
And that's actually started to take up quite a bit

00:34:26.199 --> 00:34:27.719
with some internal projects,

00:34:27.719 --> 00:34:29.959
that idea of interactive exploration.

00:34:30.520 --> 00:34:32.280
Now that's not the end goal, right?

00:34:32.280 --> 00:34:34.120
I mean, me personally,

00:34:34.120 --> 00:34:35.959
I have much bigger goals than that.

00:34:35.959 --> 00:34:39.320
That's why I'm involved in this R Consortium work group

00:34:39.320 --> 00:34:42.840
where we're trying to use R for clinical submissions

00:34:42.840 --> 00:34:43.959
straight through and through,

00:34:43.959 --> 00:34:46.840
where we got some great leads on that coming up soon.

00:34:46.840 --> 00:34:48.600
So we started with capabilities

00:34:48.600 --> 00:34:50.439
that are brought to the table

00:34:50.439 --> 00:34:53.399
that are just really difficult to replicate easily

00:34:54.040 --> 00:34:56.360
with other proprietary products.

00:34:56.360 --> 00:34:58.840
So that helped us quite a bit so far.

00:34:59.479 --> 00:35:01.159
And respect to Shiny for Python,

00:35:01.239 --> 00:35:03.159
yes, like many in the,

00:35:03.159 --> 00:35:04.840
who attended our studio conference,

00:35:04.840 --> 00:35:07.399
Joe Chang announced that I was glued to my chair

00:35:07.399 --> 00:35:09.639
trying to see where this trend would go.

00:35:10.360 --> 00:35:12.280
I think it's still early days for us

00:35:12.280 --> 00:35:14.280
in life sciences for embracing it.

00:35:14.280 --> 00:35:15.239
But at the same time,

00:35:15.239 --> 00:35:18.040
the idea of a serverless Shiny app

00:35:18.040 --> 00:35:20.360
has raised a lot of eyebrows.

00:35:20.360 --> 00:35:22.919
And certainly I'm keeping a close eye on it.

00:35:22.919 --> 00:35:23.800
And over time,

00:35:23.800 --> 00:35:27.000
I'm sure it's gonna bring some interesting insights

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:29.159
to what we can deploy.

00:35:29.159 --> 00:35:31.159
Now, it just so happens that

00:35:31.159 --> 00:35:33.879
in a lot of the workflows I'm doing at the moment,

00:35:33.879 --> 00:35:35.080
they're based in R

00:35:35.080 --> 00:35:37.239
simply because that's been a lot of what we've

00:35:37.239 --> 00:35:39.479
historically built in my particular group.

00:35:39.479 --> 00:35:40.760
But we definitely have some

00:35:40.760 --> 00:35:43.399
that are very interested in Shiny for Python

00:35:43.399 --> 00:35:44.919
and trying to see how far it takes.

00:35:44.919 --> 00:35:47.239
I just would say in life sciences,

00:35:47.239 --> 00:35:48.360
it's still pretty early days,

00:35:48.360 --> 00:35:50.280
but again, we're keeping a close eye on it.

00:35:50.280 --> 00:35:51.959
Yeah, that's what I understand.

00:35:51.959 --> 00:35:53.080
Thank you for answering those.

00:35:53.080 --> 00:35:54.120
That's super helpful.

00:35:54.120 --> 00:35:56.919
That's what I understood too for pharma industry.

00:35:56.919 --> 00:36:00.199
But I think in the long run,

00:36:00.199 --> 00:36:02.199
that might be the future for newer apps

00:36:02.199 --> 00:36:04.040
that would be probably built from scratch

00:36:04.040 --> 00:36:07.000
and not the legacy apps probably.

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:08.919
But I just want to keep an eye out

00:36:08.919 --> 00:36:11.399
on the good stuff that you and Eli Lilly is doing

00:36:11.399 --> 00:36:13.639
and learn from that along the way.

00:36:13.639 --> 00:36:14.439
So thank you.

00:36:14.439 --> 00:36:15.000
Thank you, Eric.

