about getting access to the RStudio server,

00:38:28.040 --> 00:38:30.199
getting access to the HPC cluster.

00:38:30.199 --> 00:38:31.959
How do I launch a Shiny app?

00:38:31.959 --> 00:38:32.760
Eric, help.

00:38:34.120 --> 00:38:36.600
It was almost like the copy paste of the response

00:38:36.600 --> 00:38:38.199
and I got tired of it.

00:38:38.199 --> 00:38:40.120
And when I get tired of something,

00:38:40.120 --> 00:38:41.239
that's when I'm like,

00:38:41.239 --> 00:38:42.600
I'm gonna put this down for a bit.

00:38:42.600 --> 00:38:45.399
I'm gonna focus on solving this right now.

00:38:45.399 --> 00:38:48.360
So I took the first two months of this year

00:38:48.919 --> 00:38:51.719
to produce an internal documentation portal

00:38:51.719 --> 00:38:53.959
written in Hugo with a really cool theme

00:38:54.600 --> 00:38:57.800
to document almost every type of info

00:38:57.800 --> 00:38:59.959
I thought for enabling people

00:38:59.959 --> 00:39:02.040
the ability to get started with R.

00:39:02.040 --> 00:39:03.159
I called this,

00:39:03.159 --> 00:39:05.239
and it was in collaboration with the HPC team.

00:39:05.239 --> 00:39:07.159
So they helped me along the way.

00:39:07.159 --> 00:39:09.000
But when I launched that,

00:39:09.879 --> 00:39:12.919
it made me feel like this square peg thing,

00:39:12.919 --> 00:39:15.320
now I brought value out of that to others

00:39:15.320 --> 00:39:17.399
because I took this knowledge

00:39:17.399 --> 00:39:19.080
that was in my head most of the time

00:39:19.080 --> 00:39:20.360
and I put it out there,

00:39:20.919 --> 00:39:22.520
gave links to people,

00:39:22.520 --> 00:39:26.120
and now people are sending those documentation links

00:39:26.120 --> 00:39:27.800
to others when they have questions.

00:39:27.800 --> 00:39:29.479
It's not always coming on me.

00:39:29.479 --> 00:39:31.479
So I feel fortunate that

00:39:31.479 --> 00:39:33.560
spreading that knowledge has helped.

00:39:33.560 --> 00:39:35.239
There are so many other aspects

00:39:35.239 --> 00:39:37.000
where I don't think I've spread enough yet

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:38.919
that I'm looking at the best ways of doing it.

00:39:39.479 --> 00:39:41.320
But it also helped that

00:39:41.320 --> 00:39:43.080
I've had some leadership recently

00:39:43.080 --> 00:39:47.239
that know when they can let me turn loose on something.

00:39:47.239 --> 00:39:48.840
They're confident that I'm not going to

00:39:49.399 --> 00:39:51.080
steer things in the wrong direction,

00:39:51.080 --> 00:39:53.239
that I just need a little time to ruminate

00:39:53.239 --> 00:39:55.159
and maybe try this idea out.

00:39:55.159 --> 00:39:57.320
And the risk versus reward,

00:39:57.320 --> 00:39:58.120
they tend to think,

00:39:58.120 --> 00:40:01.159
okay, the reward is greater potential here than the risk.

00:40:02.600 --> 00:40:04.600
But there are certain aspects of this

00:40:04.600 --> 00:40:05.560
I still struggle with.

00:40:05.560 --> 00:40:08.040
So really it's bringing others along

00:40:08.040 --> 00:40:11.479
and making sure not all this stuff is trapped in my head

00:40:11.560 --> 00:40:13.479
is the first thing I'm trying to address

00:40:13.479 --> 00:40:15.879
in this ongoing quest, I might say.

00:40:19.800 --> 00:40:20.520
Hope that helps.

00:40:21.879 --> 00:40:23.479
Thanks, Eric.

00:40:24.840 --> 00:40:27.479
I was waiting to see if anyone wanted to jump in there.

00:40:29.399 --> 00:40:32.360
I see, Travis, you also put a great question into the chat.

00:40:32.360 --> 00:40:33.479
Do you want to jump in next?

00:40:33.479 --> 00:40:34.840
Sure.

00:40:34.840 --> 00:40:37.639
I guess my joke question's about the Eli Lilly Twitter account.

00:40:37.639 --> 00:40:39.560
Oh, yeah, it was the first one.

00:40:39.560 --> 00:40:40.760
Oh, fine, fine.

00:40:41.800 --> 00:40:44.919
Eric, I was hoping you'd get ahold of the parody account

00:40:44.919 --> 00:40:46.919
and tweet that Eli is R only now, you know?

00:40:47.959 --> 00:40:48.760
That'd be a winner.

00:40:48.760 --> 00:40:50.840
I might even return to the bird side if that was possible.

00:40:50.840 --> 00:40:52.439
But anyway, my real question,

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:58.120
are there key ways that you want to see Eli's data stack change

00:40:58.120 --> 00:40:59.479
over the next five years, let's say?

00:41:00.199 --> 00:41:04.120
I think a lot of us that champion R at an org

00:41:04.120 --> 00:41:06.040
end up becoming R administrators

00:41:06.040 --> 00:41:08.280
and kind of like have to learn things

00:41:08.280 --> 00:41:09.959
that we didn't set out to learn.

00:41:10.600 --> 00:41:12.120
You know, I know how to write R,

00:41:12.120 --> 00:41:13.399
but I spend most of my time these days

00:41:13.399 --> 00:41:15.479
thinking about infrastructural challenges,

00:41:15.479 --> 00:41:19.639
like what's the right mix of cloud versus on-prem,

00:41:19.639 --> 00:41:22.439
particularly when we're talking about life sciences data.

00:41:22.439 --> 00:41:23.879
That gets to be a sticky question.

00:41:24.840 --> 00:41:28.280
Modern database usage is not a common thing

00:41:28.280 --> 00:41:29.959
in pharma and in CROs

00:41:29.959 --> 00:41:32.840
because of kind of software monopolies

00:41:32.840 --> 00:41:35.080
like metadata and others in that space.

00:41:36.040 --> 00:41:38.120
Do you have strategy you can share

00:41:38.120 --> 00:41:38.919
around those sorts of things?

00:41:38.919 --> 00:41:40.280
Like, what are you all thinking?

00:41:40.280 --> 00:41:43.080
Because a lot of our usage can be kind of handicapped

00:41:43.080 --> 00:41:46.199
by not being able to actually hit a real database

00:41:46.840 --> 00:41:48.120
in the way that we would like.

00:41:48.840 --> 00:41:50.280
Are you all developing on that side?

00:41:51.479 --> 00:41:53.159
Oh, I'm definitely thinking of it.

00:41:54.040 --> 00:41:58.040
And in fact, one of the earliest internal R packages

00:41:58.040 --> 00:42:00.840
I created at the company was, in essence,

00:42:00.840 --> 00:42:03.639
a wrapper to Hadley Wickham's Haven package,

00:42:03.639 --> 00:42:05.560
the imports assays that's into R.

00:42:06.439 --> 00:42:08.840
I call it Coaster, very affectionate name

00:42:08.840 --> 00:42:09.639
because it's just one of those things

00:42:09.639 --> 00:42:10.439
you might take for granted,

00:42:10.439 --> 00:42:11.959
but when you need it, you like it.

00:42:13.639 --> 00:42:16.199
I felt like I should never have had to do that.

00:42:16.199 --> 00:42:18.840
I feel like the data should not be trapped

00:42:18.840 --> 00:42:20.520
in SAS proprietary formats.

00:42:20.520 --> 00:42:22.679
This is where Eric's going to have another hot take here.

00:42:22.679 --> 00:42:24.600
So hopefully I still have a job after this.

00:42:25.560 --> 00:42:28.600
But I do think that the wave of the future,

00:42:28.600 --> 00:42:30.600
and I'm seeing some work streams around this,

00:42:30.600 --> 00:42:33.639
is looking at alternative data formats that are more open

00:42:34.280 --> 00:42:36.360
that could then be transformed

00:42:36.360 --> 00:42:40.040
into what we need for, say, a submission or other pipelines.

00:42:40.040 --> 00:42:41.159
But we're not there yet.

00:42:41.159 --> 00:42:42.520
We're definitely not there yet.

00:42:43.080 --> 00:42:44.919
And that's why I wrote that internal package.

00:42:44.919 --> 00:42:47.320
I wanted to lower the barrier of entry

00:42:47.320 --> 00:42:50.199
for people around me in the statistics group

00:42:50.199 --> 00:42:52.520
to use R for their innovative work,

00:42:52.520 --> 00:42:53.639
but not feel handcuffed

00:42:53.639 --> 00:42:56.360
because the data was in this proprietary format.

00:42:56.360 --> 00:42:57.800
It's not perfect though.

00:42:57.800 --> 00:43:01.159
We have some esoteric errors that I cannot debug

00:43:01.159 --> 00:43:04.520
because who's good at reverse engineering

00:43:04.520 --> 00:43:05.639
a proprietary format?

00:43:05.639 --> 00:43:06.360
Not me.

00:43:06.360 --> 00:43:08.439
I just try to leverage what the community has.

00:43:08.439 --> 00:43:11.560
So I think until we as an industry

00:43:12.199 --> 00:43:14.600
kind of really look ourselves in the mirror and say,

00:43:14.600 --> 00:43:16.360
this way we're capturing data

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:19.080
is not going to cut it for the long term,

00:43:19.800 --> 00:43:21.800
we're always going to have to jump through hoops.

00:43:21.800 --> 00:43:25.239
And I'm not happy about that.

00:43:25.239 --> 00:43:27.719
But I do think there's starting to get more attention

00:43:28.439 --> 00:43:30.840
on what we're seeing the general tech sector do

00:43:30.840 --> 00:43:35.560
for volumous data and easier access to data.

00:43:36.360 --> 00:43:38.199
I think the seeds are being planted,

00:43:38.199 --> 00:43:39.800
but this isn't where I want to be yet.

00:43:39.800 --> 00:43:41.560
So admittedly at Lilly,

00:43:41.560 --> 00:43:42.840
what we've been concentrating on

00:43:42.840 --> 00:43:46.199
is kind of more on the downstream effects of an analysis,

00:43:46.760 --> 00:43:48.919
making outputs interactive,

00:43:48.919 --> 00:43:51.959
giving people shiny apps to quickly explore their results.

00:43:51.959 --> 00:43:54.760
We're having more traction there immediately

00:43:54.760 --> 00:43:56.199
because that's accessible.

00:43:56.199 --> 00:43:58.760
Once you get the data into R,

00:43:58.760 --> 00:44:00.520
then we're able to turn loose on this.

00:44:00.520 --> 00:44:02.520
But this is an evolving story.

00:44:02.520 --> 00:44:03.479
And I share the pains

00:44:03.479 --> 00:44:05.879
that you've been mentioning there quite a bit.

00:44:07.239 --> 00:44:08.280
Thanks, that's a good answer.

00:44:08.280 --> 00:44:09.159
I know I've been keeping an eye

00:44:09.159 --> 00:44:11.000
on that CDISC JSON hackathon.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:12.439
You probably are aware of that as well.

00:44:12.439 --> 00:44:13.399
That seems intriguing,

00:44:13.399 --> 00:44:15.320
a way to get out of the SAS 7 BDAT

00:44:15.879 --> 00:44:17.399
kind of web that we live in these days,

00:44:17.399 --> 00:44:18.600
but we'll see.

00:44:18.600 --> 00:44:19.719
We'll see, time will tell,

00:44:19.719 --> 00:44:21.959
but it's worth watching.

00:44:21.959 --> 00:44:22.840
Thank you very much.

00:44:24.439 --> 00:44:26.760
Can you share that in the chat, Travis?

00:44:27.959 --> 00:44:29.159
Yeah, sure. I'll dig it up somewhere.

00:44:30.520 --> 00:44:31.020
Awesome.

