Thanks, Javier.

00:47:44.219 --> 00:47:47.820
Jumping through to see a few questions from Slido

00:47:47.820 --> 00:47:49.500
that I think I missed a bit earlier.

00:47:49.580 --> 00:47:52.699
And one was, sorry, scrolling up.

00:47:52.699 --> 00:47:55.659
Oh, one was being at Eli Lilly so long, Eric.

00:47:55.659 --> 00:47:57.419
What have been the biggest changes

00:47:57.419 --> 00:47:58.699
you've seen over that time?

00:48:00.620 --> 00:48:01.739
Well, there's been a lot.

00:48:03.979 --> 00:48:05.899
A lot of the change that happened

00:48:05.899 --> 00:48:08.459
that are most at forefront to me

00:48:09.340 --> 00:48:11.179
was an initiative many years ago

00:48:11.179 --> 00:48:14.459
where we tried to minimize the time

00:48:14.459 --> 00:48:16.699
from say a treatments discovered

00:48:16.699 --> 00:48:18.860
in say the discovery lab

00:48:18.860 --> 00:48:20.860
to when we can actually get that treatment

00:48:20.860 --> 00:48:23.020
out to patients to benefit from.

00:48:23.020 --> 00:48:26.540
It's kind of called minimizing that white space to get there.

00:48:27.260 --> 00:48:30.459
To do that, we had to do a lot of things differently.

00:48:30.459 --> 00:48:32.379
There has been reorgs in terms of like

00:48:32.379 --> 00:48:34.459
how trials are designed,

00:48:34.459 --> 00:48:37.580
more emphasis into other functionalities.

00:48:37.580 --> 00:48:38.939
But within statistics,

00:48:38.939 --> 00:48:41.419
it actually empowered us quite a bit

00:48:41.419 --> 00:48:43.899
to push new cutting edge algorithms

00:48:44.459 --> 00:48:47.260
for designing and for simulation

00:48:47.260 --> 00:48:50.060
and to not just do the traditional analysis

00:48:50.060 --> 00:48:51.899
for like a clinical outcome.

00:48:51.899 --> 00:48:54.459
So the fact that we got this mandate to be like,

00:48:54.459 --> 00:48:56.219
okay, we got to shorten this time

00:48:56.219 --> 00:48:59.739
that we're in this research phase or this study phase,

00:48:59.739 --> 00:49:01.899
then we had to really put all hands on deck

00:49:01.899 --> 00:49:03.979
to put out new solutions.

00:49:03.979 --> 00:49:08.540
And so that just brought innovation out of necessity,

00:49:08.540 --> 00:49:11.739
but it also opened the door for those in my group

00:49:12.139 --> 00:49:15.020
at the time to really think differently

00:49:15.020 --> 00:49:17.979
of how we're leveraging R in the design space

00:49:17.979 --> 00:49:20.139
and become one of the industry leaders

00:49:20.139 --> 00:49:21.820
in doing clinical simulation.

00:49:21.820 --> 00:49:25.500
We've definitely have really much relied

00:49:25.500 --> 00:49:28.939
on a lot of the functionalities that my colleagues have made.

00:49:28.939 --> 00:49:30.379
And I'm not gonna come here and say,

00:49:30.379 --> 00:49:33.580
I know all the ins and outs of every statistical method.

00:49:33.580 --> 00:49:35.020
That's why we have a team, right?

00:49:35.020 --> 00:49:37.659
Everybody can specialize in their key areas,

00:49:37.659 --> 00:49:39.260
but we've all been able to pitch in

00:49:39.260 --> 00:49:41.100
and be able to bring that innovation

00:49:42.060 --> 00:49:45.419
to more novel designs that can shorten that time

00:49:45.419 --> 00:49:48.139
that a patient has to be in a trial.

00:49:48.139 --> 00:49:51.100
And the industry itself still has a ways to go,

00:49:51.659 --> 00:49:55.899
but just that emphasis on let's get these treatments

00:49:55.899 --> 00:49:57.500
out to patients sooner,

00:49:57.500 --> 00:50:00.379
just organically then brought some new innovations

00:50:00.379 --> 00:50:02.300
that we were doing in statistics.

00:50:02.300 --> 00:50:04.459
And it really gave us a voice at the table

00:50:04.459 --> 00:50:07.899
that we could bring some really innovative change

00:50:07.899 --> 00:50:10.139
to how we were doing things in the past.

00:50:10.139 --> 00:50:13.260
So certainly that's been one of the higher level

00:50:13.260 --> 00:50:14.219
changes I've seen.

00:50:14.219 --> 00:50:17.419
And like I said, embracing open source

00:50:17.419 --> 00:50:20.939
in more than just a set of very simple ways,

00:50:21.580 --> 00:50:24.300
especially with R has been a big change as well

00:50:24.300 --> 00:50:27.260
because it's still not a hundred percent

00:50:27.260 --> 00:50:28.939
and it'd probably never be a hundred percent,

00:50:29.500 --> 00:50:32.379
but we've got the attention in the right places now

00:50:32.379 --> 00:50:34.300
to really build some key innovations.

00:50:34.300 --> 00:50:37.260
And I've been fortunate to be in the forefront

00:50:37.260 --> 00:50:39.739
of some of that and bringing others along the way

00:50:39.739 --> 00:50:41.419
is what I get excited about too.

00:50:44.780 --> 00:50:47.419
Thank you so much, Eric.

00:50:47.419 --> 00:50:50.780
And I know the time goes by very quickly here,

00:50:50.780 --> 00:50:53.179
but I don't think we can let today

00:50:53.179 --> 00:50:55.899
and without talking a bit about podcasting.

