So we use that every,

00:51:47.739 --> 00:51:50.620
either Tuesday or Wednesday morning or afternoon,

00:51:50.620 --> 00:51:53.179
depending on our schedules to record our voice.

00:51:53.179 --> 00:51:54.780
But, and I bring it down locally

00:51:54.780 --> 00:51:58.540
and I use a software, unfortunately not open source,

00:51:58.540 --> 00:52:00.379
but it's also the state of the art

00:52:00.379 --> 00:52:03.979
in this called Reaper to do the actual editing

00:52:03.979 --> 00:52:07.820
where I can automate a lot of the voice processing

00:52:07.820 --> 00:52:10.939
to get like the levels nice and avoid clipping

00:52:10.939 --> 00:52:13.580
and make everything kind of sound pretty,

00:52:13.580 --> 00:52:14.780
at least halfway decent.

00:52:15.340 --> 00:52:17.419
And it's just super blazing fast,

00:52:18.300 --> 00:52:21.500
you know, exit out or X out all my little ums

00:52:21.500 --> 00:52:23.899
or like, oh, I botched that person's name wrong.

00:52:23.899 --> 00:52:25.260
I do that over again.

00:52:25.260 --> 00:52:27.419
So being able to smooth all that out

00:52:27.419 --> 00:52:28.780
and do it pretty quickly,

00:52:29.340 --> 00:52:34.699
that's been my tool of choice for audio editing.

00:52:34.699 --> 00:52:37.739
It's been Reaper to bring the voice tracks in

00:52:37.739 --> 00:52:40.379
and it's a cross-platform Mac, Windows and Linux.

00:52:40.379 --> 00:52:43.020
So me being a Linux guy, I get to use that too.

00:52:43.020 --> 00:52:44.699
So that's been helpful.

00:52:44.699 --> 00:52:47.179
And then for the video side, for the Shiny Dev Series,

00:52:47.179 --> 00:52:48.540
I know that's not part of the question,

00:52:48.540 --> 00:52:51.100
but I can't not talk about the Shiny Dev Series.

00:52:52.139 --> 00:52:53.820
I record everything,

00:52:53.820 --> 00:52:56.939
whether it's a live stream or my video tutorials

00:52:57.020 --> 00:52:59.500
with OBS, Open Broadcaster Studio.

00:53:00.300 --> 00:53:02.139
It's a lot to get into at first,

00:53:02.139 --> 00:53:06.060
but actually Jim Hester, a former Posit employee,

00:53:06.939 --> 00:53:08.300
was doing a few tutorials

00:53:08.300 --> 00:53:09.820
about some of the things he was working on.

00:53:09.820 --> 00:53:12.860
And I asked him at RStudioConf a couple of years ago,

00:53:12.860 --> 00:53:14.540
hey, those are great tutorials, what are you using?

00:53:15.100 --> 00:53:17.419
He's matter of fact, oh, I'm using OBS.

00:53:17.419 --> 00:53:20.780
I'm like, OBS, isn't that like super hard to learn?

00:53:20.780 --> 00:53:22.939
He's like, oh, you'd get the hang of it.

00:53:22.939 --> 00:53:24.699
And sure enough, I got addicted to it.

00:53:24.699 --> 00:53:27.580
So now I use that for my video production

00:53:27.580 --> 00:53:29.020
and that's been a huge win for me

00:53:29.020 --> 00:53:30.699
because it's so flexible.

00:53:30.699 --> 00:53:32.939
And members of the Linux community that I follow

00:53:32.939 --> 00:53:35.820
have also supercharged OBS setups

00:53:35.820 --> 00:53:37.179
and I follow their lead

00:53:37.179 --> 00:53:40.699
and bring that into my work station over here.

00:53:40.699 --> 00:53:43.820
So OBS for video and then Reaper for the audio.

